SIMPLE: roundabout
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roundabout
<hw>Round"a*bout`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Circuitous; going round; indirect; <as>as, <ex>roundabout</ex>
speech</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have taken a terrible <qex>roundabout</qex> road.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Encircling; enveloping; comprehensive.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Large, sound, <xex>roundabout</xex> sense.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roundabout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Roundabout
<hw>Round"a*bout`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A large
horizontal wheel or frame, commonly with wooden horses, etc., on which
children ride; a merry-go-round; a carousel.</def>
<mark>[British]</mark> <rj><au>Smart.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dance performed in a circle.</def>
<rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A short, close jacket worn by boys, sailors,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A state or scene of constant change, or of recurring
labor and vicissitude.</def> <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>a <er>traffic circle</er>.</def> <mark>[Chiefly
British]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roundaboutness</ent>⟦br⟧
